                "instruction": "An Air Stagnation Advisory indicates that due to limited movement of\nan air mass across the advisory area, pollution has the potential to\nincrease to dangerous levels.                 "headline": "Air Stagnation Advisory issued January 15 at 11:45AM PST until January 20 at 4:00PM PST by NWS Pendleton OR",
                "description": "* WHAT...For the Dense Fog Advisory, visibility one half mile or\nless in dense fog. For the Air Stagnation Advisory, poor air\nquality will continue. This is due to an inversion and stagnant\nair conditions near the surface that will continue to trap\npollutants.\n\n* WHERE...Lower Columbia Basin of Washington.\n\n* WHEN...For the Air Stagnation Advisory, until 4 PM PST Tuesday.\nFor the Dense Fog Advisory, until 2 PM PST this afternoon.\n\n* IMPACTS...Poor air quality may cause issues for people with\nrespiratory problems. Low visibility could make driving conditions\nhazardous, especially along portions of I-82 and US-395.",
                "instruction": "An Air Stagnation Advisory indicates that due to limited movement of\nan air mass across the advisory area, pollution has the potential to\nincrease to dangerous levels. Persons with respiratory illness\nshould follow their physicians advice for dealing with high levels\nof air pollution during periods of stagnant air, state air quality\nagencies highly recommend that no outdoor burning occur and that\nresidential wood burning devices be limited as much as possible.\nAccording to state air quality agencies, prolonged periods of\nstagnant air can hold pollutants close to the ground, where people\nlive and breathe.                 "senderName": "NWS Twin Cities/Chanhassen MN",
                "headline": "Winter Weather Advisory issued January 15 at 1:32PM CST until January 16 at 6:00PM CST by NWS Twin Cities/Chanhassen MN",
                "description": "...WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY FOR STRONG WINDS AND BLOWING SNOW...\n\n.Strong northwesterly winds will combine with scattered snow showers\nto blow falling snow and significantly reduce visibility. Due to the\nnature of the setup, the onset of visibility reductions will occur\nquickly and create hazardous travel conditions through the day. Slick\ntravel conditions may develop.\n\n* WHAT...Snow expected. Total snow accumulations up to one inch.\nWinds gusting as high as 45 mph.\n\n* WHERE...Portions of central, south central, southwest, and west\ncentral Minnesota.\n\n* WHEN...From midnight tonight to 6 PM CST Friday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. The hazardous\nconditions will impact the Friday morning and evening commutes.\nGusty winds could bring down tree branches.",
                "instruction": "Slow down and use caution while traveling. Call 5 1 1 or visit\n511mn.org for road conditions.",

                "headline": "Cold Weather Advisory issued January 15 at 1:25PM EST until January 16 at 9:00AM EST by NWS Tallahassee FL",
                "description": "* WHAT...For the Freeze Warning for a Hard Freeze, sub-freezing\ntemperatures as low as 22 expected. For the Cold Weather Advisory,\nvery cold temperatures as low as 21 expected.\n\n* WHERE...Portions of Big Bend and Panhandle Florida.\n\n* WHEN...From 11 PM EST /10 PM CST/ this evening to 9 AM EST /8 AM\nCST/ Friday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Frost and freeze conditions could kill crops, other\nsensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor\nplumbing.",
                "instruction": "Use caution while traveling outside. Wear appropriate clothing, a\nhat, and gloves.\n\nKeep pets indoors as much as possible.\n\nMake frequent checks on older family, friends, and neighbors. Ensure\nportable heaters are used correctly. Do not use generators or grills\ninside.\n\nTake steps now to protect tender plants from the cold.\n\nTo prevent freezing and possible bursting of outdoor water pipes\nthey should be wrapped, drained, or allowed to drip slowly. Those\nthat have in-ground sprinkler systems should drain them and cover\nabove-ground pipes to protect them from freezing.",
                "response": "Prepare",

                "headline": "Cold Weather Advisory issued January 15 at 1:18PM EST until January 16 at 9:00AM EST by NWS Miami FL",
                "description": "* WHAT...For the Freeze Warning Glades and hendry counties,\nsub-freezing temperatures as low as 28 expected. For the Cold\nWeather Advisory, very cold wind chills in the lower 30s.\n\n* WHERE...Glades and Hendry Counties.\n\n* WHEN...From 3 AM to 9 AM EST Friday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Very cold temperatures can lead to hypothermia with\nprolonged exposure. Frost and freeze conditions could kill crops,\nother sensitive vegetation and possibly damage unprotected outdoor\nplumbing.",
                "instruction": "Use caution while traveling outside. Wear appropriate clothing, a\nhat, and gloves.\n\nKeep pets indoors as much as possible.\n\nMake sure outdoor animals have a warm, dry shelter, food, and\nunfrozen water.\n\nMake frequent checks on older family, friends, and neighbors. Ensure\nportable heaters are used correctly. Do not use generators or grills\ninside.\n\nTake steps now to protect tender plants from the cold.\n\nTo prevent water pipes from freezing; wrap or drain or allow them to\ndrip slowly.",

                "description": "...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in\nMississippi...Louisiana...\n\nPearl River Near Pearl River affecting Pearl River, Hancock and\nSt. Tammany Counties.\n\nFor the Lower Pearl River...including Bogalusa, Pearl River...Minor\nflooding is forecast.\n\n* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.\n\n* WHERE...Pearl River near Pearl River.\n\n* WHEN...Until early Saturday morning.\n\n* IMPACTS...At 16.0 feet, Lower portions of streets in River Gardens\nSubdivision will begin to flood.                 "instruction": "Caution is urged when walking near riverbanks.\n\nTurn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads.                 "headline": "Flood Warning issued January 15 at 9:37AM CST until January 17 at 1:12AM CST by NWS New Orleans LA",
                "description": "...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in\nMississippi...Louisiana...\n\nPearl River Near Pearl River affecting Pearl River, Hancock and\nSt. Tammany Counties.\n\nFor the Lower Pearl River...including Bogalusa, Pearl River...Minor\nflooding is forecast.\n\n* WHAT...Minor flooding is occurring and minor flooding is forecast.\n\n* WHERE...Pearl River near Pearl River.\n\n* WHEN...Until early Saturday morning.\n\n* IMPACTS...At 16.0 feet, Lower portions of streets in River Gardens\nSubdivision will begin to flood. Secondary roads to the river and\nthroughout Honey Island Swamp will remain inundated. Property in\nthe vicinity of the gage is flooded threatening about 20 homes\nalong the left bank.                 "instruction": "Caution is urged when walking near riverbanks.\n\nTurn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads.                 "headline": "Flood Watch issued January 14 at 9:49PM AKST until January 16 at 6:00PM AKST by NWS Anchorage AK",
                "description": "* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall and frozen ground\nsurface is possible.\n\n* WHERE...The following area, Southern Kenai Mtns. This includes the\ncity of Seward.\n\n* WHEN...From 9 AM AKST Thursday through Friday afternoon.\n\n* IMPACTS...Excessive runoff from rainfall, frozen ground surfaces,\nand snowmelt may result in flooding of rivers, creeks, streams,\nand other low-lying and flood-prone locations. Flooding may occur\nin poor drainage and urban areas. Snow covered drains will\nexacerbate any ponding on roadways.\n\n* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...\n- An atmospheric river will bring warmer temperatures and heavy\nrainfall  at lower elevations to the eastern Kenai Peninsula,\nincluding Seward. The long stretch of cold weather has\nresulted in frozen ground surfaces which will allow for\nincreased runoff concerns. Up to several inches of rainfall\nis expected and will lead to ponding on roadways and\nlocalized flooding in low-lying areas and areas where storm\ndrains remain covered. Expect rises on area creeks and\nrivers.\n\n- Http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood\n\n- Storm drains should be cleared of snow as much as possible.",

                "description": "* WHAT...For the Freeze Warning, sub-freezing temperatures in the\nmid 20s to near 30. For the Cold Weather Advisory, very cold\ntemperatures as low as 25 expected.\n\n* WHERE...Portions of northeast and northern Florida.\n\n* WHEN...For the Freeze Warning, from 11 PM Thursday to 9 AM EST\nFriday. For the Cold Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 9 AM EST\nFriday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Very cold temperatures can lead to hypothermia with\nprolonged exposure. Appropriate action should be taken to ensure\ntender vegetation and outdoor pets have adequate protection from\nthe cold temperatures. Young children, the elderly and the\nhomeless are especially vulnerable to the cold. Take measures to\nprotect them.",
                "instruction": "Wear appropriate clothing, a hat, and gloves.\n\nKeep pets indoors as much as possible.\n\nMake sure outdoor animals have a warm, dry shelter, food, and\nunfrozen water.\n\nMake frequent checks on older family, friends, and neighbors. Ensure\nportable heaters are used correctly.                 "description": "* WHAT...For the Freeze Warning and Cold Weather Advisory,\nsub-freezing temperatures in the low to mid 20s expected.\n\n* WHERE...Portions of northeast and northern Florida.\n\n* WHEN...For the Freeze Warning, from 11 PM Thursday to 9 AM EST\nFriday. For the Cold Weather Advisory, from 4 AM to 9 AM EST\nFriday.\n\n* IMPACTS...Very cold temperatures can lead to hypothermia with\nprolonged exposure. Appropriate action should be taken to ensure\ntender vegetation and outdoor pets have adequate protection from\nthe cold temperatures. Young children, the elderly and the\nhomeless are especially vulnerable to the cold. Take measures to\nprotect them.",
                "instruction": "Wear appropriate clothing, a hat, and gloves.\n\nKeep pets indoors as much as possible.\n\nMake sure outdoor animals have a warm, dry shelter, food, and\nunfrozen water.\n\nMake frequent checks on older family, friends, and neighbors. Ensure\nportable heaters are used correctly. Do not use generators or grills\ninside.\n\nTake steps now to protect tender plants from the cold.\n\nTo prevent water pipes from freezing; wrap or drain or allow them to\ndrip slowly.",

                "description": "SABAFC\n\nThe following message is transmitted at the request of the\nChugach National Forest Avalanche Center.\n\n...THE CHUGACH NATIONAL FOREST AVALANCHE INFORMATION CENTER HAS\nISSUED AN AVALANCHE WARNING FOR FOR THE FOLLOWING AREAS:\nANCHORAGE HILLSIDE, GIRDWOOD, PORTAGE, INTERIOR KENAI PENINSULA,\nAND THE SOUTHERN KENAI MOUNTAINS...\n\n* WHAT...The backcountry avalanche danger is HIGH. Large natural avalanches are\nlikely and human triggered avalanches are very likely. Debris\nfrom avalanches above may run into valley bottoms. Avalanche\nconditions will remain very dangerous during and immediately\nafter the storm finishes.\n\n* PRECAUTIONARY / PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...Travel in avalanche\nterrain is NOT recommended. Backcountry travelers should stay\noff and out from underneath slopes steeper than 30 degrees.\nAvalanches may run long distances.
